image_info.caption: Haematoxylin-eosin staining (Ã— 100) of the large mass biopsy sample revealed a highly cellular sample with a predominant population of discrete round cells with a pale basophilic cytoplasm and intracytoplasmic granules (purple). Each cell had central nuclei with dispersed chromatin and a single prominent nucleolus. Mild anisocytosis and anisokaryosis were present. These round cells were morphologically consistent with mast cells

Immunohistochemical expression pattern of the KIT protein (CD117) in a primary intrathoracic chest wall mast cell tumour in a dog. The KIT protein is a type III tyrosine kinase protein involved in mast cell growth and differentiation (Ã— 400). Courtesy of Thompson Phatology

text_list: The clinical staging of Case 1 showed intrathoracic mast cell disease. Thus, it can be presumed that this one of the first reported case of canine primary intrathoracic chest wall MCT. A limitation of this case study was the lack of post-mortem examination, bone marrow biopsy and buffy coat smear. A post-mortem examination and a bone marrow examination could have showed additional lesions corresponding to mast cell disease at non-pulmonary sites. However, a buffy coat smear has low sensitivity and specificity for the detection of circulating malignant mast cells [13]. 3.In the published article, the legends for the Figs. 2
